<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="366" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,150,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This new species is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1933" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1933" box="[811,1101,150,176]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Thubdora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis box="[811,927,150,176]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">T. barbata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[933,1101,150,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" refId="ref9682" refString="Meyrick, E. (1933) s. n. In: Exotic Microlepidoptera. Vol. 4. Wilts, Marlborough, pp. 353 - 384." type="book" year="1933">Meyrick, 1933</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by having a yellowish-white, triangular costal patch, but it can be distinguished by the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[798,814,186,200]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">nd</superScript>
segment of labial palpus more roughly scaled ventrally. The female genitalia can be differentiated from any previously described species by the broad and short ductus bursae, and the signum with similar lips divided by the very broader median groove.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="366" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,294,320]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Description.</emphasis>
Female (
<figureCitation box="[447,578,294,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[163,1437,417,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1437,417,1939]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Thubdora cuneiformis Park &amp; Karisch, sp. nov.: A, Adult, holotype; A1, Label; A2, Labial palpus; B, Female genitalia, GU-3898/Karisch; C, Abdomen, in SDEI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Figs. 6A, A</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[578,593,294,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,600,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-247@2.[151,1436,597,1813]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A: View from Mt. Tonkoui over the anthropogenic influenced tropical rain forest on the slopes (by T. Karisch, 25 viii 1997); B: Collecting site for light trapping with altimontane rain forest fragments at the South-Eastern slopes of Mt. Tonkoui (by T. Karisch, 25 viii 1997; C: Fragmentary secondary rain forest south of Gouédié (by T. Karisch, 20 viii 1997); D: Collecting site at the Southern border of Gouédié (by T. Karisch, 17 viii 1997)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810510/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">2</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 14.0 mm. 
<emphasis box="[840,901,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Head</emphasis>
: blackish-brown, margins paler brown.Antenna about as long as forewing; scape elongated, broadened distally; flagellum brown with some fuscous scales, whitish towards tip, slightly serrated, finely ciliate. Second palpomere of labial palpus thickened, arched, pale brown; 3 
<superScript attach="none" box="[1423,1437,366,380]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">rd</superScript>
palpomere slender, a bit longer than 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[568,584,402,416]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">nd</superScript>
palpomere, upturned, brown, paler dorsally. 
<emphasis box="[1083,1164,402,428]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Thorax</emphasis>
: Dark brown. Hind tibia roughly scaled, shiny, dark brown, with a pale-yellow scales distally, pale yellow ventrally; spurs grayish yellow. Forewing ground color dark brown, with a violet lustre in basal half; antemedian band with two black dots; costa slightly arched in basal ¼, with small, yellowish, trapezoidal costal patch on 4/5 of costa; apex rounded; termen straight; fringe blackish, shiny. Hind wing ground color grayish brown, darker towards outer margin; apex more or less obtuse; fringe grayish brown, with narrow, pale yellow basal line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" box="[199,1220,618,645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis box="[199,305,618,644]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[320,409,618,644]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[163,1437,417,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1437,417,1939]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Thubdora cuneiformis Park &amp; Karisch, sp. nov.: A, Adult, holotype; A1, Label; A2, Labial palpus; B, Female genitalia, GU-3898/Karisch; C, Abdomen, in SDEI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
): Dark brown dorsally. Spinous zones well-developed on dorsal surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis box="[199,390,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[404,493,654,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1963,1987]" captionTargetBox="[163,1437,417,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1437,417,1939]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Thubdora cuneiformis Park &amp; Karisch, sp. nov.: A, Adult, holotype; A1, Label; A2, Labial palpus; B, Female genitalia, GU-3898/Karisch; C, Abdomen, in SDEI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810520/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
): Abdominal sternite VIII narrowed distally, deeply emarginated into U-shape medially. Ostium bursae broadly concave. Antrum bowl-shaped, membranous, about 1/5 the length of ductus bursae. Ductus bursae broadened overall beyond narrowed conjunction with antrum, nearly parallel-sided. Corpus bursae ovate, about half the length of ductus bursae; signum with similar lips anteriorly and posteriorly, divided by the very broader median groove.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" box="[199,376,834,860]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Male unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,729,870,897]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" box="[199,729,870,897]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,870,896]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,491,870,897]" name="Ivory Coast" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Ivory Coast</collectingCountry>
(Montagne District).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="366" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,150,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,906,932]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named after the Latin, - 
<emphasis box="[612,690,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">cuneus</emphasis>
(= wedge), referring to the wedge-shaped costal patch on the forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
